[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    141[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The corpus-ingestion pipeline is triggered by EventBridge on a schedule plus event-driven updates ("New PubMed releases, new guideline publications, and new institutional content trigger corpus ingestion. EventBridge routes these events to the ingestion pipeline."). EventBridge is at-least-once. Duplicate causes are standard: scheduled-rule drift across time zones, overlapping rules in multi-region deployments, event-bus replays after a failover, manual re-runs during operator response to an earlier failure, NCBI E-utilities partial responses that get retried. Each duplicate triggers a fresh Step Functions execution that re-ingests the same PubMed record set, re-embeds chunks (the most expensive step at $200-$2,000 per full rebuild by the recipe's own estimate), and writes to OpenSearch. The worst case is not cost; it is an OpenSearch index with duplicate chunks for the same paper, which then show up as duplicate citations in answers. The recipe does not discuss idempotency for the ingestion pipeline. Same recurring Chapter 2 pattern as Recipes 2.4, 2.5, 2.6. This is the first time the pattern applies to a batch-ingestion workflow rather than a per-patient clinical trigger, but the same conditional-write discipline applies.[K
